Now I have all the information needed to write a comprehensive implementation plan. Let me produce the final design.

---

## Implementation Plan: Custom Theme System for T3 Code Editor

### 1. Architecture Overview

The theme system introduces three layers:

1. **Shared type definitions** (`packages/shared/src/theme.ts`) -- Plain TypeScript types and constant data for the three built-in themes. No Effect/Schema dependency; follows the pattern of `git.ts` and `shell.ts`.
2. **Enhanced `useTheme` hook** (`apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`) -- Extends the existing external-store pattern to track both the base mode (`"light" | "dark" | "system"`) and an optional named theme ID. Applies CSS custom properties to `document.documentElement.style`.
3. **Theme selector component** (`apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`) -- A visual picker with color swatches, integrated into the existing Appearance section of `apps/web/src/routes/_chat.settings.tsx`.

### 2. Theme Type Definition in `packages/shared`

#### New file: `packages/shared/src/theme.ts`

This file exports plain TypeScript types and the three built-in theme objects. It has zero runtime dependencies (no Effect, no Node APIs). The pattern mirrors `git.ts` -- just pure functions and constants.

```ts
/** Semantic color slots that a named theme can override. */
export interface ThemeColors {
  // Core palette (map to existing CSS vars)
  background: string;
  foreground: string;
  accent: string;
  accentForeground: string;
  primary: string;
  primaryForeground: string;

  // Region-specific (new CSS vars)
  sidebarBackground: string;
  sidebarForeground: string;
  editorBackground: string;
  editorForeground: string;
  terminalBackground: string;
  terminalForeground: string;
  statusBarBackground: string;
  statusBarForeground: string;
}

/** Whether the theme should activate the `.dark` class. */
export type ThemeBase = "light" | "dark";

export interface ThemeDefinition {
  /** Unique stable identifier, e.g. "t3-dark". */
  id: string;
  /** Human-readable label shown in the UI. */
  label: string;
  /** Determines the `.dark` class toggle and fallback variable set. */
  base: ThemeBase;
  /** CSS color values (hex, oklch, rgb, etc.) that override the defaults. */
  colors: ThemeColors;
}

export const BUILT_IN_THEMES: readonly ThemeDefinition[] = [
  {
    id: "t3-dark",
    label: "T3 Dark",
    base: "dark",
    colors: {
      background: "oklch(0.145 0.013 260)",
      foreground: "oklch(0.92 0.01 260)",
      accent: "oklch(0.25 0.015 260)",
      accentForeground: "oklch(0.92 0.01 260)",
      primary: "oklch(0.588 0.217 264)",
      primaryForeground: "#ffffff",
      sidebarBackground: "oklch(0.13 0.015 260)",
      sidebarForeground: "oklch(0.85 0.01 260)",
      editorBackground: "oklch(0.145 0.013 260)",
      editorForeground: "oklch(0.92 0.01 260)",
      terminalBackground: "oklch(0.12 0.015 260)",
      terminalForeground: "oklch(0.90 0.005 260)",
      statusBarBackground: "oklch(0.588 0.217 264)",
      statusBarForeground: "#ffffff",
    },
  },
  {
    id: "t3-light",
    label: "T3 Light",
    base: "light",
    colors: {
      background: "#ffffff",
      foreground: "oklch(0.27 0.02 260)",
      accent: "oklch(0.95 0.01 260)",
      accentForeground: "oklch(0.27 0.02 260)",
      primary: "oklch(0.488 0.217 264)",
      primaryForeground: "#ffffff",
      sidebarBackground: "oklch(0.97 0.005 260)",
      sidebarForeground: "oklch(0.35 0.02 260)",
      editorBackground: "#ffffff",
      editorForeground: "oklch(0.27 0.02 260)",
      terminalBackground: "oklch(0.97 0.005 260)",
      terminalForeground: "oklch(0.27 0.02 260)",
      statusBarBackground: "oklch(0.488 0.217 264)",
      statusBarForeground: "#ffffff",
    },
  },
  {
    id: "t3-midnight",
    label: "T3 Midnight",
    base: "dark",
    colors: {
      background: "oklch(0.10 0.02 270)",
      foreground: "oklch(0.88 0.02 250)",
      accent: "oklch(0.18 0.03 270)",
      accentForeground: "oklch(0.88 0.02 250)",
      primary: "oklch(0.65 0.25 270)",
      primaryForeground: "#ffffff",
      sidebarBackground: "oklch(0.08 0.025 275)",
      sidebarForeground: "oklch(0.78 0.02 250)",
      editorBackground: "oklch(0.10 0.02 270)",
      editorForeground: "oklch(0.88 0.02 250)",
      terminalBackground: "oklch(0.07 0.025 275)",
      terminalForeground: "oklch(0.85 0.015 250)",
      statusBarBackground: "oklch(0.12 0.04 270)",
      statusBarForeground: "oklch(0.80 0.02 250)",
    },
  },
] as const;

/** Lookup a built-in theme by ID. Returns undefined for unknown IDs. */
export function getBuiltInTheme(id: string): ThemeDefinition | undefined {
  return BUILT_IN_THEMES.find((t) => t.id === id);
}

/** All valid built-in theme IDs. */
export const BUILT_IN_THEME_IDS = BUILT_IN_THEMES.map((t) => t.id);

/**
 * Map from ThemeColors keys to CSS custom property names.
 * Core properties override existing vars; region-specific ones are new.
 */
export const THEME_COLOR_TO_CSS_VAR: Record<keyof ThemeColors, string> = {
  background: "--background",
  foreground: "--foreground",
  accent: "--accent",
  accentForeground: "--accent-foreground",
  primary: "--primary",
  primaryForeground: "--primary-foreground",
  sidebarBackground: "--sidebar-background",
  sidebarForeground: "--sidebar-foreground",
  editorBackground: "--editor-background",
  editorForeground: "--editor-foreground",
  terminalBackground: "--terminal-background",
  terminalForeground: "--terminal-foreground",
  statusBarBackground: "--status-bar-background",
  statusBarForeground: "--status-bar-foreground",
};
```

#### Package export registration in `packages/shared/package.json`

Add a new subpath export entry following the existing pattern:

```json
"./theme": {
  "types": "./src/theme.ts",
  "import": "./src/theme.ts"
}
```

### 3. How Named Themes Interact with Light/Dark Mode

The key design decision is that a named theme **replaces** the simple `"light" | "dark" | "system"` mode selection, rather than layering on top of it. The relationship works as follows:

- The **stored value** changes from `Theme = "light" | "dark" | "system"` to `ThemeSelection = "light" | "dark" | "system" | string` (where any other string is treated as a named theme ID like `"t3-midnight"`).
- When a named theme is selected, its `base` property (`"light" | "dark"`) determines whether the `.dark` class is toggled on `document.documentElement`. This preserves the existing `@variant dark` CSS mechanism, so all the dark-mode overrides in `index.css` continue to work correctly.
- The named theme's `colors` are then applied as inline CSS custom property overrides on `document.documentElement.style`, which take precedence over both the `:root` and `@variant dark` declarations.
- When reverting to `"light"`, `"dark"`, or `"system"`, all named-theme inline style overrides are removed, and the system behaves exactly as it does today.
- The `resolvedTheme` return value from `useTheme()` remains `"light" | "dark"` for backward compatibility, so all existing consumers (ChatMarkdown, DiffPanel, DiffWorkerPoolProvider, ChatView) work without changes.

### 4. Enhanced `useTheme` Hook

#### File: `apps/web/src/hooks/useTheme.ts`

The existing file is modified in-place. Key changes:

**a) Import theme data from shared:**
```ts
import {
  getBuiltInTheme,
  THEME_COLOR_TO_CSS_VAR,
  type ThemeColors,
} from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
```

**b) Widen the `Theme` type:**
```ts
type Theme = "light" | "dark" | "system" | string;
```

The `getStored()` function stops validating against only three values and returns whatever string is in localStorage (falling back to `"system"` for empty/null).

**c) New `applyThemeColors` function:**
```ts
function applyThemeColors(themeId: string | null): void {
  const el = document.documentElement;
  // Always clear previous named-theme overrides first
  const allVarNames = Object.values(THEME_COLOR_TO_CSS_VAR);
  for (const varName of allVarNames) {
    el.style.removeProperty(varName);
  }

  if (!themeId) return;
  const definition = getBuiltInTheme(themeId);
  if (!definition) return;

  for (const [key, cssVar] of Object.entries(THEME_COLOR_TO_CSS_VAR)) {
    const value = definition.colors[key as keyof ThemeColors];
    if (value) {
      el.style.setProperty(cssVar, value);
    }
  }
}
```

**d) Modify `applyTheme`:**
```ts
function applyTheme(theme: Theme, suppressTransitions = false) {
  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.classList.add("no-transitions");
  }

  const definition = getBuiltInTheme(theme);
  const isDark = definition
    ? definition.base === "dark"
    : theme === "dark" || (theme === "system" && getSystemDark());

  document.documentElement.classList.toggle("dark", isDark);
  applyThemeColors(definition ? theme : null);

  if (suppressTransitions) {
    document.documentElement.offsetHeight;
    requestAnimationFrame(() => {
      document.documentElement.classList.remove("no-transitions");
    });
  }
}
```

**e) Extended hook return type:**
The hook gains a new `activeThemeId` field:
```ts
export function useTheme() {
  const snapshot = useSyncExternalStore(subscribe, getSnapshot);
  const theme = snapshot.theme;

  const definition = getBuiltInTheme(theme);
  const resolvedTheme: "light" | "dark" = definition
    ? definition.base
    : theme === "system"
      ? snapshot.systemDark ? "dark" : "light"
      : theme === "dark" ? "dark" : "light";

  // activeThemeId is the named theme ID if one is active, or null
  const activeThemeId: string | null = definition ? theme : null;

  const setTheme = useCallback((next: Theme) => {
    localStorage.setItem(STORAGE_KEY, next);
    applyTheme(next, true);
    emitChange();
  }, []);

  useEffect(() => {
    applyTheme(theme);
  }, [theme]);

  return { theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme, activeThemeId } as const;
}
```

This preserves full backward compatibility: `{ theme, setTheme, resolvedTheme }` all work identically for existing consumers. The new `activeThemeId` is additive.

### 5. CSS Custom Property Integration

#### Existing variables that get overridden by named themes

The theme `colors.background` maps to `--background`, `colors.foreground` maps to `--foreground`, etc. These override the values defined in `:root { ... }` and `@variant dark { ... }` blocks because inline styles on `document.documentElement` have higher specificity than stylesheet declarations.

#### New region-specific CSS variables

The following new CSS variables need to be **consumed** (not defined in `index.css` -- they are only set by named themes):
- `--sidebar-background`, `--sidebar-foreground`
- `--editor-background`, `--editor-foreground`
- `--terminal-background`, `--terminal-foreground`
- `--status-bar-background`, `--status-bar-foreground`

These should be wired into `index.css` with sensible fallbacks using the CSS `var()` fallback syntax:

```css
/* Add to index.css inside @theme inline block */
--color-sidebar: var(--sidebar-background, var(--background));
--color-sidebar-foreground: var(--sidebar-foreground, var(--foreground));
```

This is where the Tailwind v4 `bg-sidebar` and `text-sidebar-foreground` classes already reference `--color-sidebar` and `--color-sidebar-foreground`. By defining them with fallbacks to the base variables, the sidebar component picks them up automatically when a named theme sets `--sidebar-background`.

Similarly, add to `@theme inline`:
```css
--color-editor: var(--editor-background, var(--background));
--color-editor-foreground: var(--editor-foreground, var(--foreground));
--color-terminal: var(--terminal-background, var(--background));
--color-terminal-foreground: var(--terminal-foreground, var(--foreground));
--color-status-bar: var(--status-bar-background, var(--primary));
--color-status-bar-foreground: var(--status-bar-foreground, var(--primary-foreground));
```

This approach:
- Does NOT break any existing `@variant dark` rules
- Provides graceful fallbacks when no named theme is active (all region vars fall back to existing base vars)
- Lets Tailwind v4 generate utility classes like `bg-terminal`, `text-editor-foreground`, etc.
- The inline style overrides set by `applyThemeColors` take priority over both `:root` and `@variant dark` declarations

### 6. Theme Selector Component

#### New file: `apps/web/src/components/ThemeSelector.tsx`

This component renders a grid of theme cards, each showing preview color swatches. It follows the existing UI patterns:
- Uses `cn()` for class merging
- Uses the same border/card styling as the settings page sections
- Uses Lucide icons where appropriate

```tsx
// Conceptual structure (not actual JSX -- just the design)

import { BUILT_IN_THEMES, type ThemeDefinition } from "@t3tools/shared/theme";
import { cn } from "~/lib/utils";

interface ThemeSelectorProps {
  activeThemeId: string | null;
  onSelect: (themeId: string) => void;
}

